The %#NewSWModule#% functional flow block diagram shows the activites that %#NewSWModule#% will support and be use for. This diagram is a high level diagram that shows the highest level activities for the %#NewSWModule#% 's use in relation to the actors who will use and interact with tem as well as the resulting data from the activity and the overall data flow.

The Functional IPO Diagram is used to visualize the functions needed for this module. The (Input-Process-Output) diagram is a high-level diagram used for systems analysis that visually describes processes with the description of each function in words shown from the implementation perspective. show this as a flow provides a general construct to systematically identify, describe and relate the functions performed by either the user or system to meet their goal. An IPO diagram shows a process's key inputs and resulting outputs after a set of functions. The IPO analysis concept was extended for %#NewSWModule#% for functional analysis by using the Hatley and Pirbhai (H-P) for real-time control systems. The %#NewSWModule#% functional decomposition used the (H-P) IPO analysis technique shown in the diagram.

The %#NewSWModule#% shows the functional requirements flowed down from the subsystem to the %#NewSWModule#% module. This diagram is useful we relating the functional allocations from system to subsystem, to module.

This diagram shows the prioritization of the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% Function Prioritized by Generation functions and in which generation of %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% Function Prioritized by Generation design they will be implemented in. This approach is used to focus the team on ensuring that the critical functions get implemented first.
Each generation is planned such that the most important functionality is implemented in Gen 1 and Gen 2. In practicality Gen 4 and Gen 5 could be combined to accelerate schedule and certain functions might not get implemented.
Contained here in are the function diagrams and function descriptions.

This diagram shows the prioritization of the %#NewSWModule#% Use Cases by generation. This approach is used to focus the simplest behaviors for implementation first tn ensure that the critical functions implemented have the right behaviors.
Each generation is planned such that the easiest to implement use cases are implemented in Gen 1 and Gen 2. In practicality Gen 4 and Gen 5 could be combined or canceled if the users determine the behaviors have been fulfilled by previous generations.
The deployment diagram shows the deployment of the components across the various devices in the module.
The Design Diagram shows the breakdown of the %#NewSWModule#% module into its components.
